r v john terry was a 2012 criminal trial in england which involved the former chelsea and england captain, terry, being tried for racially abusing qpr's anton ferdinand. terry was found guilty of a single charge of racially abusing ferdinand and was sentenced to a four-match suspension, later reduced to two matches on appeal. the conviction has been widely criticised as an example of britain's " racist justice system". background the trial arose from an incident that took place during a premier league match between chelsea and queens park rangers on 11 october 2012. ferdinand, who was playing for qpr
at the time, was allegedly subjected to a tirade of racist abuse by terry, who was then chelsea captain. the abuse included references to ferdinand's black skin and alleged that he was "going to score with his brown face". the football association (fa) investigated the matter and charged terry with a single offence of racially abusing ferdinand. the trial began on 10 december 2012 at southwark crown court and ended with terry being found guilty on 2 march 2013. he was subsequently sentenced to a four-match suspension, later reduced to two matches on appeal. reception the conviction of john terry
pharmaceutical medicine is a medical discipline concerned with the diagnosis, treatment and prevention of diseases using pharmaceutical drugs. pharmaceuticals are substances created and used to diagnose, cure, prevent or ameliorate disease. pharmaceuticals are often classified into two categories: prescription drugs, which must be prescribed by a healthcare professional, and over-the-counter (otc) drugs, which can be purchased without a prescription. pharmaceuticals are generally classified according to their mechanism of action. therapeutic pharmaceuticals are medications intended to cure or improve a patient's symptoms. non-therapeutic pharmaceuticals are those that do not cure or improve symptoms but may have other purposes such as blocking
