edward holbrook derrick (1898–1976) was an australian historian and professor of history at the university of melbourne. derrick was born in 1898 in melbourne, victoria, australia to alfred holbrook derrick, a solicitor and judge, and his wife, marion (née holbrook). he was educated at scotch college and then at the university of melbourne, where he obtained a bachelor of arts in 1922 and a master of arts in 1924. he then undertook postgraduate studies at the university of london, where he obtained a doctor of philosophy degree in 1926. after returning to australia, derrick began his teaching career at the
university of melbourne in 1927 as an assistant lecturer. he became a full professor in 1945 and held that position until his retirement in 1961. during that time, he served as dean of the faculty of arts from 1951 to 1953 and vice-chancellor from 1957 to 1959. in 1964, he was made an honorary fellow of the university of melbourne. derrick's academic interests lay primarily in australian history, and he published extensively on that topic. his most important works include the history of victoria (3 vols., 1937–1950), the history of new south wales (2 vols., 1952–1954), the history of queensland
