a harlot's progress (also known as the history of a woman whorish) is a novel by the english author john cleland. published in 1748, it tells the story of a young woman's journey from innocence to vice. the novel was initially published under the pseudonym fanny hill. upon its publication, it caused considerable public scandal, and cleland was prosecuted and fined. the book has been considered controversial and has been banned in several countries. the story is narrated by the heroine, esther verena, who begins as an innocent girl but gradually becomes involved in a world of prostitution. she is
robert harvey (born 23 may 1955) is a scottish former footballer who played as a midfielder in the football league for darlington, rochdale and stockport county. harvey started his career with darlington, before joining rochdale in 1980. he helped the club to promotion to the football league in 1983, and remained with rochdale for four seasons, during which time he made 111 appearances. he then signed for stockport county, where he made 110 appearances before retiring in 1988. after retiring from playing, harvey became a football coach. he has worked with youth teams in scotland and england, and has also
margaret masson hardie hasluck m.b.e. (1944) (1899-1991) was a british physician, who was the first female chief medical officer of england and wales. hasluck was born on 18 january 1899 in bradford, england. after graduating from the university of liverpool with a medical degree in 1923, hasluck worked as a doctor in her home country before being appointed as the first female chief medical officer of england and wales in 1974. during her tenure, hasluck oversaw a number of important medical reforms, including the establishment of the national health service (nhs) and the introduction of immunisation programmes. hasluck retired from
alexander alexandrovich bolonkin (; 14 march 1933 – 25 october 2014) was a russian mathematician, known for his work in combinatorics, probability theory, and mathematical physics. he was also a professor of mathematics at the moscow state university. bolonkin was a member of the russian academy of sciences and the american mathematical society. bolonkin was born on 14 march 1933 in moscow, ussr. he graduated from minsk state university with a diploma in mathematics in 1954. he then studied at the moscow state university under the supervision of lev landau and maxim kolmogorov, receiving his doctorate in 1957. from 1957
to 1959 he was a post-doctoral fellow at princeton university. bolonkin returned to the moscow state university where he became a professor in 1973. in 1991 he became head of the department of mathematics there. he retired from that post in 2009. bolonkin's research focused on combinatorics, probability theory, and mathematical physics. some examples of his work include: - the bolonkin–weil conjecture (1962), which concerns lattices with an odd number of nodes; - the bolonkin–levin theorem (1978), which states that certain lattices have more than one minimal model; - the birch and swinnerton–dyer conjecture (1998), which concerns the number of
dom francisco de almeida , also known as francisco de almeida the younger, was a portuguese soldier and explorer who played a prominent role in the portuguese conquest of ceylon (now sri lanka) in 1505. he is credited with founding colombo, then the capital of portuguese ceylon. almeida was born in 1483 or 1484 in lisbon, portugal to a cultured and wealthy family. he entered the service of king manuel i of portugal in 1500, and soon distinguished himself by his bravery and martial skills. in 1502, he accompanied the portuguese army that invaded morocco, and he distinguished himself during
cadmus of miletus (, kádmos ho milésios) was a pre-socratic philosopher from the city of miletus in ionia, who is credited with being the first philosopher. he is known for his theory of four elements, which was influential in the development of greek science. cadmus was born c. 612 bc to the wealthy family of thebes. cadmus had two older brothers, philemon and polydorus, and two younger sisters, aglaea and autonoe. cadmus' father died when cadmus was young, and he and his brothers were raised by their mother. cadmus was educated in the ways of the world by the master
of rhetoric, philemon, who taught him how to speak persuasively and argue logically. cadmus also learned astronomy, botany, and music from his sisters. cadmus met thales while he was in exile on the island of samos. thales taught cadmus about the natural world and explained that everything in it is made up of small parts that are related to one another. thales also taught cadmus about mathematics and astronomy. cadmus returned to miletus and began to teach philosophy. he believed that philosophy should be able to explain everything that can be understood by rational thought, including the nature of gods
harrison ngau laing is a malaysian environmentalist, writer, and activist. he is the founder of the save malaysia movement, and has been involved in environmental activism since the early 1990s. harrison ngau laing was born in kuala lumpur, malaysia in 1962. he attended the university of california, berkeley, where he earned a b.a. in environmental science in 1984. after graduation, ngau laing worked as a research scientist for the world wildlife fund (wwf) in washington d.c. he returned to malaysia in 1990 and founded the save malaysia movement (smm) as an environmental advocacy group. the smm is dedicated to protecting
malaysia's rainforests, coral reefs, and other natural resources. ngau laing has written extensively on environmental issues in malaysia and around the world. his books include the destruction of nature: ecology and politics in twentieth-century malaysia (2004), co-authored with kaarina wiik; the silent rainforest: the fight for borneo's forests (1998); and the great forest swindle: how china's theft of malaysian timber is threatening the environment (1994). he has also contributed to numerous journal articles and newspaper articles on environmental topics. harrison ngau laing is a member of the international union for conservation of nature (iucn), the malaysian green party, and the
hypofrontality is a state of decreased cerebral blood flow due to an abnormality in the distribution of blood flow within the brain. it is a characteristic feature of multiple sclerosis (ms) and may be associated with cognitive impairment, fatigue, and a reduced quality of life. hypofrontality is a feature of multiple sclerosis (ms), which is a chronic neurological disorder. it is characterized by decreased cerebral blood flow, which can lead to poor cognitive function, fatigue, and a reduced quality of life. there is currently no cure for ms, but treatments that improve symptoms can help reduce the risk of further
disability. multiple sclerosis is a complex disorder that results from damage to the myelin sheath surrounding the neurons in the brain and spinal cord. the damage leads to loss of nerve function in parts of the body, including the eyes, ears, hands, and feet. the cause of ms is unknown, but it is believed to be caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors. symptoms typically begin gradually and then worsen over time. the most common symptoms are pain in the limbs or joints, numbness or tingling, vision problems, problems with balance or coordination, and difficulty speaking or understanding
