spindle (sub-glacial polar ice navigation, descent, and landing system) is a robotic vehicle designed and built by the uk antarctic research programme (ukarp) for use in the antarctic continent. it is a four-wheeled, amphibious vehicle, propelled by an electric motor, capable of operating at high speeds over snow and ice. the spindle project is one of the ukarp's flagship projects, and has been in development for over 10 years. spindle is designed to provide a safe and efficient means of accessing remote areas of the antarctic continent, and to allow researchers to carry out research activities without having to travel
on foot or by helicopter. spindle was first tested in antarctica in 2006, and has since been used by ukarp researchers to carry out a wide range of tasks in the antarctic environment. in 2008, spindle was used to transport supplies to the british research station at amundsen–scott south pole station, and in 2009 it was used to transport personnel and equipment to the british research station at palmer station. spindle has proved to be a reliable and versatile vehicle, able to handle a wide range of conditions in the antarctic environment. its amphibious design means that it can easily
