hrizea of bogdănei , also rendered as hrizaea, ( romanian: "hrizea de bogdănei" or "hrizaea de jos") is a romanian white wine grape variety that is grown mainly in the jiu valley in the southwestern region of romania. the grape was first described in 1784 by the french botanist pierre-joseph redouté as a possible parent of the chardonnay wine grape. however, the exact parentage of hrizea of bogdănei remains unknown. today, hrizea of bogdănei is most commonly used to produce dry table wine. however, it can also be used to make sweet wines if allowed to ripen on the lees
