otto van veen, also known by his nickname oude veen, (october 12, 1853 – october 3, 1928) was a dutch artist who is considered one of the most important painters in the history of dutch painting. he was a painter, sculptor, printmaker, and etcher who spent most of his career in amsterdam. van veen was born in amsterdam into a family of painters. he studied at the royal academy of fine arts in the hague from 1873 to 1875 before moving to paris to continue his studies at the académie julian from 1875 to 1878. in 1880 he returned to
amsterdam and became a member of the dutch association of painters and sculptors. in 1886 he traveled to italy, france, and spain, where he studied the works of the old masters. he returned home in 1889 and began teaching at the academy. van veen is best known for his paintings of peasants and workers, many depicting scenes from his native netherlands. his paintings are noted for their naturalistic detail and unsentimental portrayals of life. he was also a successful sculptor, producing works such as the potato eaters (1889), which was donated to the museum of modern art in new york
