community-based conservation is a conservation movement that emphasizes the importance of community involvement in conservation. the goal of community-based conservation is to create partnerships between local communities and conservation organizations in order to conserve natural resources while also benefiting local communities. community-based conservation is a relatively new concept, and there is still much debate surrounding its effectiveness. some argue that community-based conservation is a more effective way to conserve resources than traditional conservation methods, while others claim that it is not as effective as traditional methods. however, the main goal of community-based conservation is to create partnerships between local communities
and conservation organizations in order to conserve natural resources. the concept of community-based conservation was first proposed by professor jarold lindeman in the early 1990s. lindeman was a professor at the university of british columbia and he believed that traditional conservation methods were not working well enough to protect natural resources. he proposed the idea of community-based conservation, which emphasized the importance of community involvement in conservation. since its inception, community-based conservation has been successful in creating partnerships between local communities and conservation organizations. for example, the klamath mountains community conservation alliance (kmcca) is a community-based organization that was created
