charles cuthbertson learmonth dfc & bar (2 december 1912 – 2 july 1988) was a senior british airman during the second world war. he was one of the most decorated raf officers of the war, receiving 38 awards, including the distinguished flying cross, bar and distinguished service order. charles learmonth was born on 2 december 1912 in newcastle upon tyne, england. in 1933 he joined the royal air force as an airman. in 1939 he became a flying officer and in 1941 he was commissioned. in 1942 he received a distinguished flying cross for flying in support of the allied
kingdom identity ministries (kim) is a self-described "prosperous, international ministry" with a "broad message of hope." the organization is led by pastor terry jones, who has been labeled a "rabid anti-semite" by the anti-defamation league. kim was founded in 1985 and has grown to include churches and ministries in more than 30 countries. the ministry's stated mission is "to proclaim the gospel of jesus christ and to equip believers to impact their communities for the glory of god." kim also operates an international relief and development organization, operation feed the children. kim has been criticized for its views on judaism,
which some have labeled as anti-semitic. in 2005, jones was featured on an episode of the documentary series "the new world order", which explored conspiracy theories about jewish control of world affairs. the following year, kim burned a copy of the quran – a move that sparked protests in several muslim countries. in july 2016, kim announced that it was canceling its plans to stage a full-blown theatrical production of the biblical epic "the book of jonah" in protest of what it described as "the global jewish conspiracy." terry jones was born in cedar rapids, iowa, on november 12, 1951.
stefan wyszyński (3 august 1901 – 28 may 1981) was a polish statesman and prime minister. he served as the sixth prime minister of poland from 17 may 1970 until his death, and was one of the architects of the solidarity movement. stefan wyszyński was born in the town of wisła, then part of austria-hungary, on 3 august 1901. he joined the polish legions in 1918, and fought in the polish–soviet war. after the war, he studied law at the university of warsaw. he became a member of the polish united workers' party in 1923, and was elected to the
sejm (parliament) in 1926. in 1939, wyszyński fled to london to escape nazi persecution. he served as poland's ambassador to britain from 1940 to 1943, during world war ii. after world war ii, wyszyński served as poland's minister of agriculture from 1947 to 1951. he became deputy prime minister in 1951, and served in that position until he was appointed prime minister by president stanisław mikołajczyk on 17 may 1970. wyszyński's term as prime minister was marked by political turmoil and economic decline. his government introduced wide-ranging reforms, including economic liberalization and social welfare programs. however, these measures were unpopular
