the constitutional act of the realm of denmark, sometimes referred to as the constitution of denmark or the danish constitution, is the supreme law of denmark. it was enacted on 5 june 1849 by the great powers who were gathered in vienna at the congress of vienna after the napoleonic wars. the act establishes a constitutional monarchy, with a monarch who is both head of state and head of government, as well as a unicameral parliament. the current constitution was adopted in 1953, replacing an earlier version from 1849. the danish constitution establishes a constitutional monarchy with a monarch who
